Interpretation:

Confusion Matrix: The confusion matrix shows how the model’s predictions match up against the actual values:

Improve: For the “Improve” class, the model correctly predicted “Improve” 109 times and incorrectly predicted “Worsen” 13 times.

Worsen: For the “Worsen” class, the model correctly predicted “Worsen” 30 times but also incorrectly predicted “Improve” 30 times.

Class Error: The class error rate is the proportion of times the model was incorrect for each class. For “Improve”, the error rate is about 10.66%, which means the model is relatively good at predicting improvements. For “Worsen”, however, the error rate is 50%, indicating that the model is only as good as random guessing when it comes to predicting this outcome.

test_data <- na.omit(test_data)
test_data <- test_data[!is.na(test_data$Music.effects), ]
rf_mod <- randomForest(factor(Music.effects) ~., # Set tree formula
                         data = train_data, # Set data set
                         ntree = 200,
                         nodesize = 1,
                         mtry = 12) # Set number of trees to use
rf_preds <- predict(rf_mod, test_data, type = "prob") # Create predictions for random forest model

# Convert predictions to classes, using 0.5
rf_pred_class <- rep("Improve", nrow(rf_preds))
rf_pred_class[rf_preds[,2] >= 0.5] <- "Worsen"

t <- table(rf_pred_class, test_data$Music.effects) # Create table
confusionMatrix(t, positive = "Worsen") # Produce confusion matrix

Applying a XGBoost model to the Music Effects dataset:

library(xgboost)


train_data[, 1:32] <- lapply(train_data[, 1:32], as.numeric)

dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(train_data[, 1:30]), label =  as.numeric(as.factor(train_data$Music.effects)) - 1)

test_data[, 1:32] <- lapply(test_data[, 1:32], as.numeric)

dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_data[, 1:30]), label =  as.numeric(as.factor(test_data$Music.effects)) - 1)
set.seed(111111)
bst_1 <- xgboost(data = dtrain, # Set training data
               
               nrounds = 100, # Set number of rounds
               
               verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
               
               objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
               eval_metric = "auc",
               eval_metric = "error")

Interpretation:

The model has an accuracy of 73.91%, which is above the no information rate of 63.77%. This indicates the model’s predictions are better than random chance. Class 1 is predicted with 60% sensitivity and class 2 with 81.82% specificity. Positive predictive value is 65.22%, and negative predictive value is 78.26%. Balanced accuracy is 70.91%, showing relatively equal performance in identifying both classes. The kappa score of 0.4255 suggests moderate agreement between predictions and actual values. The model’s accuracy is statistically significant with a p-value of 0.04928, just below the 0.05 threshold.

# Create a contingency table
contingency_table <- table(my_data$Fav.genre, my_data$Insomnia)

# Convert the table to a data frame
heatmap_data <- as.data.frame.matrix(contingency_table)

# Add row names as a new column
heatmap_data$Genre <- rownames(heatmap_data)

# Reshape the data to a long format
heatmap_long <- melt(heatmap_data, id.vars = "Genre", variable.name = "InsomniaLevel", value.name = "Frequency")

# Create the heatmap
ggplot(heatmap_long, aes(x = InsomniaLevel, y = Genre, fill = Frequency)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Music Genres and Insomnia",
       x = "Insomnia Level", y = "Music Genre")

From this heatmap, we can interpret the following:

Darker shades represent a higher frequency of occurrences in our dataset. For instance, the darkest shade in the “Rock” row suggests that many respondents who listen to rock music reported a high level of insomnia.

Lighter shades represent a lower frequency of occurrences. For example, in the “Classical” row, lighter shades across the insomnia levels suggest that fewer respondents who listen to classical music reported those levels of insomnia.

The distribution across insomnia levels for each genre can give us an idea of the potential impact of that genre on sleep quality. If a music genre shows consistently darker colors at higher levels of insomnia, it might suggest a correlation where listeners of that genre report higher insomnia levels. Which in turn has a higher potential of affecting the listeners mental health.

Conversely, genres like “Pop” and “Metal” show a more spread out distribution of color intensity across the insomnia levels, indicating a more varied response in reported insomnia levels among their listeners.
